data.content:
Here are the three breaking changes and their fixes:

### 1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` on record structs is now an error
C# 13 prohibits `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` because the synthesized `Equals`/`GetHashCode` only compared the first element, which was silently wrong. Change to a plain `struct`:

```csharp
[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]
struct Buffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

### 2. `Generator.cs` — `unsafe` context now flows into iterators
In C# 12, iterator methods were implicitly *safe* even inside an `unsafe class`. C# 13 lets the `unsafe` context flow in — but `yield return` inside an unsafe context is illegal. Remove `unsafe` from the class; mark only the local function:

```csharp
class DataGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<int> Generate()
    {
        yield return 1;
        Process();
        unsafe static void Process()
        {
            int* p = stackalloc int[10];
        }
    }
}
```

### 3. `Resolver.cs` — Span overload resolution ambiguity
.NET 9 adds implicit conversions between arrays and spans, changing overload resolution. The empty collection expression `[]` is now ambiguous between `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`. Fix by casting:

```csharp
static void Main()
{
    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);
}
```
